name: Lauren Gemelli
tweet:
Let‚Äôs talk COVID convalescent plasma donation. 
.
The human body is a miracle. You can donate up to once per week, up to eight times in three months. A lot more frequently than whole blood donation. During the donation the machine returns your blood cells and platelets to your body, so it‚Äôs not as taxing to your system as a whole blood donation. 
.
Each donation can help up to three COVID-19 patients. 
.
I was diagnosed on March 24. I rode it out at home, quarantined, for three weeks. I developed a very robust antibody response. To be eligible to donate you need a count of 330. My count was 2970 ‚Äî nine times the minimum count needed to donate. 
.
After I was diagnosed, I was scared. Very scared. But I wanted to spin the experience into something positive if I could. I wanted to help. I signed up for every study, filled out every survey. Columbia, Mount Sinai became my new BFFs. When New York Blood Center started taking convalescent plasma donations, I signed up immediately. 
.
At the time, very early on in the pandemic, we didn‚Äôt know if convalescent plasma would work. But there was the POSSIBILITY of it working, and that was enough of a reason for me to donate. It only cost me some time and some slight discomfort (ok, a full panic attack and feelings of claustrophobia during my first donation ‚Äî in addition to getting stuck,) but once I knew what to expect it became very routine. 
.
Over the next six months, I donated convalescent plasma a total of nine times. That‚Äôs 27 people I could help. 
.
It felt really good to feel like I was doing something ‚Äî anything ‚Äî to help. 
.
Look. I‚Äôm an organ donor. I am very comfortable in sharing my body (which I feel is just a rental anyway) if it can help save a life. Not everyone feels this way, and that‚Äôs ok. 
.
But, if you had COVID, if you still have antibodies ‚Äî please consider donating your plasma. Cases are rising, plasma can be shipped to where it‚Äôs needed. 
.
I‚Äôm happy to answer any questions you may have. 
.

name: Lia (she/her), Lia Schaffner
tweet:
Today, I donated blood for the first time today. 
And I‚Äôm not saying this or posting about it because I‚Äôm trying to gain likes and followers or get attention. I‚Äôm doing this to tell you that it‚Äôs one of the most easiest things to do if you are at least 17 and meet the medical requirements (which you can look up online).
All you have to do is make an appointment at a donation center near you and once you arrive, the process is fairly easy and simple. In fact. The process of registering was longer than donating the blood itself. 
It took 10 minutes to donate the blood and at the end, I was so surprised. Because not only was it quick, but I felt fine afterward. You‚Äôd think seeing the blood leaving your body would give you multiple side effects, but no, the only thing I felt was a bit hungry and they provided the snacks and juice. 
Knowing that something in your body has the ability to save peoples lives is something to be grateful for. We are all living on this planet, together. And I believe our purpose to help others and if you can, then why wouldn‚Äôt you?
Yes its just a small second of a pinch on your finger (to check if you have enough iron in your blood) and a tiny bit of pain on your arm to draw the blood (the same kind of feeling when you get your blood tested when you visit the doctor); but it‚Äôs worth it, when you think about the lives you are saving. Every day, hospitals need blood. For emergencies, surgeries, etc. People need blood to survive and will die without blood. That‚Äôs a fact. And right now, the only way to make blood is in living bodies. We are walking ‚Äúwaterfalls‚Äù, we are factories that make necessities for free. 
If you‚Äôre healthy, at least 17 and are near a blood donation center, I don‚Äôt see an excuse not to donate blood. (I am terrified of needles and have used that excuse to not donate and I regret that a lot, but really, technology and science have improved to make things like this easy and almost painless). It‚Äôs just an hour of your time. All it has to be is your decision to save lives.

tweet:
AJ's sweet smile gives us the extra motivation to find him a match! Recently diagnosed with a rare form of myeloid leukemia and T-cell lymphoma, he needs a blood stem donation from an unrelated donor, and currently, there are no matches on the @bethematch_nybc registry. DNA also plays an important role in the matching process, since patients are mostly likely to match with donors who share their ethnic background. AJ is of Filipino descent, which means his donor is more likely to come from this community. Unfortunately, Filipinos are significantly underrepresented on the registry. To join the registry, please sign up at join.bethematch.org/JOIN4AJ or TEXT JOIN4AJ TO 61474

name: Michael Cassara
tweet:
Today I joined the #GallonClub at @newyorkbloodcenter / #GiveBloodNYC! I had never donated blood before this year, but with significantly heightened need (and increased free time) I have been going as frequently as allowed since earlier this year, and I intend to continue for as long as I'm able. 

Every time I give, I do it for those who cannot: the FDA needs to continue to abolish its discriminatory policies and allow gay men, sex workers, and others to donate blood based on their *actual* safety practices and not reject them due to antiquated presumption. And I donate for cancer patients and others in need, including the many warriors in my life. If you're able to donate, please consider it - with so little up to us at present, it's a powerful feeling to know that you're actively saving lives.

name: Darya Karelina
tweet:
You can save lives even if you're not a frontline worker üë©‚Äç‚öïÔ∏è.

This year I began doing something that I haven't done before. In 34 years of my life, I never donated blood.

And do you know why?

Because I knew nothing about it!

Only when I began working at the hospital, I learned how important and scarce it is. Huge thanks to people from @newyorkbloodcenter
that I've been working with on organizing blood drives. They taught me a lot.

ü©∏One donation can potentially save up to 3 lives.
ü©∏Every 2 seconds, someone in the US needs blood
ü©∏Less than 38% of the population is eligible to donate blood or platelets

And the list goes on.

I'm eligible and healthy. The only regret I have is that I just started doing it. And the reason for it was a lack of education about it. Since I learned more about it, I not only donate blood but signed up for the organ donation program in case if something happens to me.

That's why I'm using my platform to share it with you.

If you can, please donate. This small act of kindness can save someone's life ‚ù§Ô∏è.

tweet: This morning I donated Convalescent Plasma at the @newyorkbloodcenter to help those suffering from COVID-19. name: Joe Yang
tweet:
On March 20, I tested positive for covid. Thankfully, my symptoms were mild and I‚Äôve been symptom free since then. 
A few friends told me that some hospitals were exploring convalescent plasma treatments - taking plasma from people who‚Äôve recovered and infusing into critically ill covid patients, the hope being that the antibodies in the plasma would help those patients recover more quickly. 
I was originally hesistant as I don‚Äôt like needles and was worried that I might contract something at the donation center and bring it back to my family. After reading numerous stories of victims and families affected, I couldn‚Äôt sit on the sidelines anymore.

Yesterday, I took the leap and donated plasma at the NY Blood Center. The plasma will be tested for antibodies and if there are enough antibodies detected, would go toward covid patients. If not, then would either go toward research or other patients who need the plasma. 
@newyorkbloodcenter

Questa foto non vinceraÃÄ il primo premio in bellezza ma spero in efficacia percheÃÅ vuole ricordarci di donare il sangueü©∏ 
Per essere idonei servono alcune precise caratteristiche che condivido qui percheÃÅ a me piuÃÄ volte ne sono mancate alcune:
-non essere anemici
chissaÃÄ quanti di noi non sanno di esserlo almeno un poÃÅ. Per evitare questa carenza che non fa mai bene un po‚Äô di carne rossa (poca ma buona) o in alternativa pesci, legumi e verdure che aiutano, o supporti chimici come ultima chance.
-non aver partorito da poco, o essere incinta
-essere in un preciso momento lontano dal ciclo
-essere lontani da viaggi in paesi tropicali
-pesare piuÃÄ di 50 kg
-non avere specifiche malattie/assunzioni di farmaci
-tendenzialmente essere dai 18 ai 60 anni
-avere il desiderio di fare un gesto che possa aiutare gli altri andando oltre la pigrizia o la sensazione poco piacevole di farsi infilare un piccolo ago sul braccio (per i piuÃÄ paurosi pensate che a chi serve quel sangue ha dovuto far molto piuÃÄ di questo).
Guardate questo elenco e se capite che voi potreste essere idonei andate a donare, altre persone vorrebbero ma non possono farlo e prenderebbero volentieri il vostro posto.

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
Today is Pregnancy and Infant Loss Remembrance Day 2020. Today, we would like to honor a very special recipient, who is now not only an advocate, but a donor herself. Gillian needed 86 blood, platelet and plasma products to survive when she hemorrhaged during childbirth and required an emergency hysterectomy. After losing her child, she and her husband Lou have decided to become advocates of blood donation, to help those in need, and to inspire others who have experienced this loss to keep going. We are continually amazed by their story, their love and the joy they bring not only to our community, but to the world. Today, we honor you Gillian, and are inspired by your continued acts of kindness. #nybloodcenter

.

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
Meet Ariel - blood recipient, and blood donation advocate. "On March 30, 2012, as I was dropping my daughter off at school, I walked around to the trunk of my car and all of a sudden, a taxi recklessly ran into me from behind. Instead of another day at the office, I was in an ambulance. Instead of listening to the morning traffic report, I was strapped to a stretcher being transferred to a trauma center. 
.
From that point on, as word spread about the accident, everyone offered to help in any way imaginable. People have a wonderful desire to want to assist those in need. I was being well taken care of by medical personnel, but what could the rest of us do? The answer soon came to all of us: Give blood. 
.
To date, I have had 11 operations and received over 70 units of blood. The human body can only hold about 14 pints. That means that somewhere out there 70 people took the time to sit in a donor‚Äôs chair and gave a unit of blood. I‚Äôll never know or be able to thank these 70 people who saved my life. But the least I can do is lend my name to the efforts of those collecting blood donations to replenish and increase our national supply. I want to inspire at least 70 friends, relatives, and members of the broader community to contribute blood. 
.
Then I‚Äôll know that I will have ‚Äúpaid forward‚Äù to others who may one day need blood. Not everyone can give for a variety of reasons, medical and other, but the gift of everyone who does give means so much. Those who can‚Äôt donate can support, volunteer and recruit. You WILL save a life, just as someone‚Äôs blood donation helped save mine." #nybloodcenter
.
.

name: Leah Hansen-Montalbano
tweet:
Today in creepy cool news!

I already made my next appointment. I swear I don‚Äôt have some weird fetish, the thought or sight of blood actually makes me dizzy. But my O+ blood type is super in demand so I feel donation is something I should do regularly and it‚Äôs really not that big a deal.

Here are some facts about O+ blood from The Red Cross:

- Type O+ blood is given to patients more than any other blood type, which is why it‚Äôs considered the most needed blood type.
- 38% of the population has O+ blood, making it the most common blood type.
- Over 80% of the population has a positive blood type and can receive O+ blood. That‚Äôs another reason it‚Äôs in such high demand.
- Type O+ blood is one of the first to run out during a shortage due to its high demand.

name: Centraljerseygirl95
tweet:
There is no substitute for human blood ü©∏. Blood is vital to our survival as it carries nutrients throughout our bodies (among other things). There are many reasons why someone might need a transfusion. These reasons include illnesses and accidents. Many who are eligible to donate do not do so. Donating blood does not harm you and it can literally save lives. Blood transfusions saved the life of someone very important to me years ago. I have been donating blood since I was old enough and I will continue to as long as I can. @newyorkbloodcenter has always been great with helping me through the donation process. You can choose to donate at one of their blood drives or by making an appointment at one of their donor centers. 

If you‚Äôre lucky, you may even get an email like this one alerting you that your donation has been routed to a particular place for use! You will not always get such an email, but it is nice to know that your donation truly had a purpose.  You even earn points for each donation and those points can be redeemed for prizes!  My points always expire because I forget about them, but if you would like free stuff you should consider donating blood. 

To check you eligibility or to find a drive or donor center near you, please visit:  https://www.nybloodcenter.org .

P.S. this is not some sort of sponsored or paid advertisement. I honestly believe in the importance of blood donation. I figure that although I have A+ blood which can only go to folks with A+ or AB+, that my donation frees up a donation of O+ or O- blood which are more versatile and rare.  Thank you for coming to my Ted Talk ü§ó

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
Maybe you have heard of double red cell donations, or maybe you've heard it called an automated red cell donation. Either way, it's doubling up on the giving! With an automated red cell donation, you can donate two units with each visit! When giving a whole blood donation, the collection needs to be sent to the lab to separate the blood components, and then the red cells need to be filtered. With automated red cell donation, the red cells are separated and filtered immediately, making them readily available, after routine testing, for the patients who desperately need them. This type of donation can be given every 112 days. To learn more about this type of donation, and to find out if you are eligible to give automated red cells, call us at 1.800.933.2566 or visit nybc.org! #nybloodcenter

name: Cooley's Anemia Foundation
tweet:
New York Blood Center is part of New York Blood Center Enterprises (NYBCe), serving over 75 million people across the U.S. In addition to New York Blood Center, the enterprise also includes Community Blood Center of Greater Kansas City, Blood Bank of Delmarva, Rhode Island Blood Center, Memorial Blood Center, Nebraska Community Blood Bank and New Jersey Blood Services.
.
In addition to blood centers all across the U.S., NYBCe is also a research facility, including Lindsley F. Kimball Research Institute (LFKRI) and the National Center for Blood Group Genomics (NCBGG). Through LFKRI and NCBGG, our team participates and studies various blood diseases, including the pathophysiology of thalassemia and other diseases caused by genetic red cell disorders to help with patients with thalaassemia. Each day, our team strives to not only impact lives in our local hospitals, but to make breakthroughs for the blood industry, and thalassemia community (amongst many others) as a whole. In addition, NYBCe conducts research in numerous blood-related fields, including transfusion medicine, cell therapy, hematology, infectious diseases, and epidemiology. #nybloodcenter #newyorkbloodcenter

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
Meet AJ, a miracle baby who needs our help New York!  After trying for so long to conceive, his parents were finally blessed with their beautiful baby boy earlier this year. AJ defied the odds and stole their hearts with his smiles, giggles, and endless perfection. But at just 9-months-old, things suddenly took a turn for the worst.
.
AJ began rejecting his food and bottles ‚Äì and what little he did eat had a hard time staying down. Typically, a bustling ball of energy, AJ also seemed especially fatigued. Concerned, his parents began trying to problem-solve with his pediatrician.
.
In early October, with his condition failing to improve, and on their pediatrician‚Äôs advice, his parents took him to the emergency room. The rest of the day blurred by with flashing lights, numerous tests, a rotation of nurses, and mounting anxiety. Soon, AJ was diagnosed with a rare form of myeloid leukemia and T-cell lymphoma.
.
In order to be cured, AJ needs a blood stem cell donation from an unrelated donor. However, he doesn‚Äôt currently have any matches on the Be The Match Registry¬Æ. AJ‚Äôs parents are now searching for another miracle ‚Äì someone to save his life.
DNA also plays an important role in the matching process, since patients are mostly likely to match with donors who share their ethnic background. AJ is of Filipino descent, which means his donor is more likely to come from this community. Unfortunately, Filipinos are significantly underrepresented on the registry.
.
Thousands of blood cancer and blood disease patients like AJ need your help. You could literally be their cure ‚Äì you could be the miracle AJ‚Äôs parents are hoping for. Join the registry today at join.bethematch.org/JOIN4AJ or TEXT JOIN4AJ to 61474
.
.
.

tweet:
Area hospitals and academic medical centers including @nychealthsystem, @northwellhealth, @nyphospital, @weillcornell, @columbiamed, @mountsinainyc, @montefiorehealthsystem, and @catholichealthservicesli are joining forces with New York Blood Center (NYBC) to increase blood donations. Temporary blood shortages are not uncommon during summer and winter holidays each year, but the COVID-19 pandemic has created a chronic shortage across the country that shows no sign of improving. This reality is particularly dangerous given the looming uncertainty surrounding the pandemic‚Äôs trajectory over the course of this winter.
.
New York‚Äôs healthcare system requires 1,500 donations each day to treat patients ranging from trauma victims to newborn babies and their mothers to cancer patients. Prior to the pandemic, donors could stop by community blood drives at convenient locations, but nearly all high schools, colleges, offices and other community groups have had to cancel their blood drives due to COVID-19. Blood donors can now make appointments to visit donor centers, but donations are at just 65% of pre-pandemic levels - well below what is needed by hospitals and patients in our area. tweet:
Repost from @newyorkbloodcenter
‚Ä¢
Area hospitals and academic medical centers including @nychealthsystem, @northwellhealth, @nyphospital, @weillcornell, @columbiamed, @mountsinainyc, @montefiorehealthsystem, and @catholichealthservicesli are joining forces with New York Blood Center (NYBC) to increase blood donations. Temporary blood shortages are not uncommon during summer and winter holidays each year, but the COVID-19 pandemic has created a chronic shortage across the country that shows no sign of improving. This reality is particularly dangerous given the looming uncertainty surrounding the pandemic‚Äôs trajectory over the course of this winter.
.
New York‚Äôs healthcare system requires 1,500 donations each day to treat patients ranging from trauma victims to newborn babies and their mothers to cancer patients. Prior to the pandemic, donors could stop by community blood drives at convenient locations, but nearly all high schools, colleges, offices and other community groups have had to cancel their blood drives due to COVID-19. Blood donors can now make appointments to visit donor centers, but donations are at just 65% of pre-pandemic levels - well below what is needed by hospitals and patients in our area. Read more at nybc.org/news
.
.

My Sunday morning... visiting the local friendly vampires at the @newyorkbloodcenter Grand Central location. I was actually shocked that I was able to donate today!! I get periodic emails from them saying they urgently need more of my blood type, and I would absolutely donate more often, but for various reasons, I haven‚Äôt been eligible for nearly 3 years now... since the last time I posted a photo like this, in fact! Getting sick with a cold before my appointment, twice for too-low iron levels (hello, iron supplements!), too-recent antibiotic use, and my favorite, travel to a malaria-endemic island (my 2019 dive trip to Indonesia)‚Äîthat one gets you a full-year ban on donating. As much as I feel kinda guilty that I haven‚Äôt been a regular donor‚Äîsince I‚Äôm part of that small population that‚Äôs both willing & able‚ÄîI can appreciate that they‚Äôre being scrupulously careful with blood donor screenings.
.

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
Meet Kyle! In February 2017, at 15 months old, was diagnosed with a very rare and potentially fatal disease called Severe Aplastic Anemia. This disease attacks the bone marrow and causes the body‚Äôs blood values to deplete and eventually become non-existent. Kyle is one of the youngest patients to ever be diagnosed and treated for this disease. It has been a long and arduous road however with a multitude of blood and platelet transfusions, chemo therapy, numerous surgical procedures, a bone marrow transplant and more medications than we can mention, Kyle is now in a good place in his treatment. Despite this fact, this disease makes it that he will forever be at risk of needing transfusions in the future. A major part of Kyle‚Äôs treatment was an abundance of blood and platelet transfusions that would not have been possible without dedicated donors! Thank you for giving to help kids like Kyle! #nybloodcenter

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
‚ÄúWhether he is donating or raising awareness, Mainali's goal has always been clear. He wants to save lives by giving something of himself.‚Äù Congrats to dedicated donor Arjun Mainali on achieving 22 donations during 2020, and for receiving the New York Blood Center Presidents Award! Throughout his life, Arjun, who is from Nepal, has donated on 6 continents in 17 countries; from Ireland to Haiti, then on to Rwanda, all at his own expense. In 2020, he made 19 donations with us!
.
Arjun's children have his blood running through their veins, but he also considers the recipients of his donations family as well, and he is proud. "I have a family around the world," said Mainali, who immigrated to the U.S. in 2000. Of his trips abroad to make donations, he recalled one time he traveling to the United Kingdom for a blood donation and then flew back within a day!
.
This year, while in the middle of making a platelet donation, he received a special call, and the timing could not have been more perfect. In his own words, here's what happened:
‚ÄúAround 12 o‚Äô clock on November 24, 2020, I was donating two units of platelets to New York Blood Center. At 1:07, the staff at the center called me. "A 30-years-old patient needs platelets. Your platelet‚Äôs HLA matches hers. Can you donate either today or tomorrow?‚Äù I told her that I was donating blood in Melville Blood Donor Center through the nurse who was taking out my platelets. At that time, Trima Accel Platelets Pheresis Machine showed the required time as 118 minutes. What a coincidence! All the nurses were amazed. My platelets instantly came in handy to save the patient. I felt glad."
.
Thank you so much Arjun, for your continued dedication to helping those in need all around the world, and right here in our own community as well!
.
.
.
 #nybloodcenter

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
Brothers, King and Mesiah Singh, were both born with a rare blood disease known as G6PD.  This disease causes red blood cells to break down in response to certain medications, infections, or other stressors.  Unfortunately, there is no cure for this rare disease and the only life-saving treatment is a blood transfusion; the only way to keep the boys alive. Additionally, King, at the age of 2, was also diagnosed with high-risk acute lymphoblastic leukemia (blood cancer). During his 3 ¬Ω years of chemotherapy treatment, numerous platelet and red blood cell transfusions helped save his life and because of this King is cancer free. Join us to donate in honor of these brave, rare disease warriors today at nybc.org/kingmesiah
.

name: Prince Wilhelm Chang
tweet:
After donating 500cc or 2 units of pRBCs of automated blood cell, you should treat yourself with some salty delicious Japanese Bento boxes. Please donate blood to #newyorkbloodcenter because there is a critical shortage of blood for those who need it.
Who can make an automated red cell donation?

To qualify as an automated red cell donor, males need to be at least 5'1 and weigh at least 130 lbs. Females must be at least 5'5" and weigh at least 150 lbs. This is because men and women have different total blood volumes and because of this difference, the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) has established different donor requirements. You can make an automated red blood cell donation every 112 days or 16 weeks.

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
September is #SickleCellAwareness month. This disease affects millions worldwide, mainly people of African descent, but also people of Hispanic, South Asian, and Middle Eastern ancestry. It is caused by a single genetic mutation that affects the shape of the oxygen carrying red blood cells, making it difficult for the red blood cells to get through small blood vessels, clogging the blood flow, and cutting off oxygen delivery to the organs. Sickle red blood cells die early, causing shortage of red cells and anemia with some cells disintegrating in the circulation, releasing toxic forms of hemoglobin that can cause tissue injury. The shortage of oxygen delivery to the organs and chronic tissue injury can lead to serious complications, including stroke and irreversible organ damage. Patients with sickle cell disease can develop antibodies that cause a reaction to blood transfusions. To reduce the risk of developing more antibodies with negative outcomes, patients need to be more closely matched with special blood donors, but there aren‚Äôt many.  Only 1.7% of donations are able to be used for sickle cell patients. Become a blood donor today and help patients fighting Sickle Cell! #nybloodcenter
.
.

name: NoFo Momma ‚Äî Meg Howard
tweet:
‚ô•Ô∏èS A V E  3  L I V E S :‚ô•Ô∏è
.
Two years ago, we nearly lost my father to a freak accident that left him with a ruptured spleen and severe internal bleeding. He required 9 units of blood, donated by complete strangers, üôèüèºüòáand this helped save his life.
.
Each year since, I have donated blood with @newyorkbloodcenter as a way to honor the donors that saved my dad and to pay life forward. Today, I brought my sister with me for her first blood donation ever!
.
In the U.S. only 3% of the population donates blood. The most common response I hear from people who don‚Äôt donate, is that they are scared of needles.  While, I can understand your hesitation, I promise you that the pinch is quick and relatively painless. And, if you ever found yourself in need of a life-saving blood transfusion, you would have to rely upon people who overcame their own needle trepidation to donate to save your life. It helps put things into perspective when you think about it that way.
.
The COVID pandemic has depleted an already limited blood supply across the country, and more donors are needed each day. I would like to share a few interesting facts about blood donation with you to encourage you to schedule an appointment to donate:
.
üíâ Just 1 donation can save up to 3 lives.
.
üíâEvery 2 seconds, someone requires a blood transfusion.
.
üíâWe go through approximately 43,000 pints of blood/day in U.S. hospitals.
.
üíâ Blood donations actually improve YOUR health: donating lowers your risk of cancer, decreases your chance of obesity, improves your heart health and can help reduce the risk of liver and pancreas damage.
.
üíâ As modern science has not found a synthetic blood substitute and blood cannot be manufactured in any way, the only viable resource of this life-saving fluid is from humans that are able and willing to donate ‚Äî like YOU!
.
To learn more about blood donation or to find out where to donate, check out @newyorkbloodcenter [if you‚Äôre in NY] or @americanredcross for nationwide resources.
.
And please consider saving 3 lives, like my dad‚Äôs! Thank you. With lots of love & gratitude - Meg üíú

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
Meet Tom ‚Äì a dedicated donor who went from giving whole blood to giving platelets when we ran pop-up apheresis drives at the Howell Elks Lodge. And Melissa - a dedicated team member and avid advocate! Melissa met Tom on her very first blood drive in her new role on our team. As nervous as she was, she knew she had a job to do - teach our donors about more ways to save lives, and that is certainly what she did! After talking with Tom about the need for platelets and how to become a donor, Tom made the jump from just giving whole blood in Toms River to becoming a regular platelet in Howell. We were so excited when we recently received this photo of their reunion! We are so grateful for the dedication of our not only our donors, but our team members who reach out to educate donors, and create lasting friendships along the way!  #nybloodcenter

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
Chris is a medically retired US Marine, heart transplant recipient, stroke survivor, and now a Motivational speaker.  While in the Marine Corps, Chris went into heart failure and suffered 3 strokes.  He had 2 open heart surgeries, the first to put in a heart pump, an LVAD, to keep him alive while he waited for a heart transplant, and the second on April 9, 2013 when he received his new heart.  Chris is now pursuing a career in Motivational speaking and helping others in a similar health situation, both civilian and Military. Donors like you provide the essential blood, platelets and plasma needed for recipients like Chris. Thank you for donating! #NationalBloodDonorMonth #nybloodcenter

name: Prince Wilhelm Chang
tweet:
After donating 500cc or 2 units of pRBCs of automated blood cell, you should treat yourself with some salty delicious Japanese Bento boxes. Please donate blood to #newyorkbloodcenter because there is a critical shortage of blood for those who need it.
Who can make an automated red cell donation?

To qualify as an automated red cell donor, males need to be at least 5'1 and weigh at least 130 lbs. Females must be at least 5'5" and weigh at least 150 lbs. This is because men and women have different total blood volumes and because of this difference, the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) has established different donor requirements. You can make an automated red blood cell donation every 112 days or 16 weeks.

name: Rob G
tweet: For around 15 years I have tried to take time to donate platelets periodically. Then on November 30th, 2011 my son was born with a low platelet count. It was scary. Thankfully the nurses, doctors and staff stepped up providing Nick with multiple platelet transfusions while he continued his stay in the NICU for two weeks as his numbers stabilized. I had always heard how giving blood saved lives, but now I had experienced it first hand. So now I always make sure to celebrate his birthday by giving back. So If you can donating blood, platelets, plasma, then do it.  It definitely can save lives. (And you get all the Lorna Dooned and apple juice you want!) #givebloodsavelives #giveplatelets #newyorkbloodcenter #paramusbloodcenter @newyorkbloodcenter

tweet:
Repost from @newyorkbloodcenter
‚Ä¢
Area hospitals and academic medical centers including @nychealthsystem, @northwellhealth, @nyphospital, @weillcornell, @columbiamed, @mountsinainyc, @montefiorehealthsystem, and @catholichealthservicesli are joining forces with New York Blood Center (NYBC) to increase blood donations. Temporary blood shortages are not uncommon during summer and winter holidays each year, but the COVID-19 pandemic has created a chronic shortage across the country that shows no sign of improving. This reality is particularly dangerous given the looming uncertainty surrounding the pandemic‚Äôs trajectory over the course of this winter.
.
New York‚Äôs healthcare system requires 1,500 donations each day to treat patients ranging from trauma victims to newborn babies and their mothers to cancer patients. Prior to the pandemic, donors could stop by community blood drives at convenient locations, but nearly all high schools, colleges, offices and other community groups have had to cancel their blood drives due to COVID-19. Blood donors can now make appointments to visit donor centers, but donations are at just 65% of pre-pandemic levels - well below what is needed by hospitals and patients in our area. Read more at nybc.org/news
.
.

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
Meet Kyle! In February 2017, at 15 months old, was diagnosed with a very rare and potentially fatal disease called Severe Aplastic Anemia. This disease attacks the bone marrow and causes the body‚Äôs blood values to deplete and eventually become non-existent. Kyle is one of the youngest patients to ever be diagnosed and treated for this disease. It has been a long and arduous road however with a multitude of blood and platelet transfusions, chemo therapy, numerous surgical procedures, a bone marrow transplant and more medications than we can mention, Kyle is now in a good place in his treatment. Despite this fact, this disease makes it that he will forever be at risk of needing transfusions in the future. A major part of Kyle‚Äôs treatment was an abundance of blood and platelet transfusions that would not have been possible without dedicated donors! Thank you for giving to help kids like Kyle! #nybloodcenter
.

name: Cooley's Anemia Foundation
tweet: Hey everyone, @newyorkbloodcenter here, and we're excited to be taking over the account today! Did you know that every 2 seconds, someone needs blood in the U.S.? New York Blood Center is one of the largest independent, community-based non-profit blood centers in the U.S. Each day, we serve thousands of community members across New York and beyond. 1,500 donations are needed DAILY to support New York's hospitals! #nybloodcenter #NationalBloodDonorMonth #newyorkbloodcenter

name: Cooley's Anemia Foundation
tweet:
Due to COVID-19, the way we collect blood has dramatically changed. The convenience of being able to walk down the hallway at your school, workplace or local community location has changed. Many of our beloved blood drive hosts have not been able to host us. At this time, New York Blood Center is encouraging donors, especially our youth, to join us to donate at a local blood center. If we are not able to encourage our high school and college age donors to give at their school, we are potentially facing long-term effects on the blood supply. We need Gen Z to step up and save more lives with us, and join us in the fight! #nybloodcenter #NationalBloodDonorMonth #GiveBloodChallenge #newyorkbloodcenter 
.
*This photo was taken prior to COVID-19. All donors must wear masks at this time.

name: Cooley's Anemia Foundation
tweet:
New York Blood Center is part of New York Blood Center Enterprises (NYBCe), serving over 75 million people across the U.S. In addition to New York Blood Center, the enterprise also includes Community Blood Center of Greater Kansas City, Blood Bank of Delmarva, Rhode Island Blood Center, Memorial Blood Center, Nebraska Community Blood Bank and New Jersey Blood Services.
.
In addition to blood centers all across the U.S., NYBCe is also a research facility, including Lindsley F. Kimball Research Institute (LFKRI) and the National Center for Blood Group Genomics (NCBGG). Through LFKRI and NCBGG, our team participates and studies various blood diseases, including the pathophysiology of thalassemia and other diseases caused by genetic red cell disorders to help with patients with thalaassemia. Each day, our team strives to not only impact lives in our local hospitals, but to make breakthroughs for the blood industry, and thalassemia community (amongst many others) as a whole. In addition, NYBCe conducts research in numerous blood-related fields, including transfusion medicine, cell therapy, hematology, infectious diseases, and epidemiology. #nybloodcenter #newyorkbloodcenter

name: Cooley's Anemia Foundation
tweet:
Diversity in our blood donor base is extremely important to providing blood to those in need. Certain African American and Hispanic/Latino patients, including those who have rare blood types or medical conditions necessitating multiple blood transfusions, require very closely matched blood products. Many times, these blood products can only be found in donors with the same racial or ethnic heritage. There is also a greater prevalence of type O blood in African American, and Hispanic/Latino populations, and this blood type is the most requested by hospitals.  #newyorkbloodcenter #NationalBloodDonorMonth #GiveBloodChallenge #newyorkbloodcenter
.

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
Meet AJ, a miracle baby who needs our help New York!  After trying for so long to conceive, his parents were finally blessed with their beautiful baby boy earlier this year. AJ defied the odds and stole their hearts with his smiles, giggles, and endless perfection. But at just 9-months-old, things suddenly took a turn for the worst.
.
AJ began rejecting his food and bottles ‚Äì and what little he did eat had a hard time staying down. Typically, a bustling ball of energy, AJ also seemed especially fatigued. Concerned, his parents began trying to problem-solve with his pediatrician.
.
In early October, with his condition failing to improve, and on their pediatrician‚Äôs advice, his parents took him to the emergency room. The rest of the day blurred by with flashing lights, numerous tests, a rotation of nurses, and mounting anxiety. Soon, AJ was diagnosed with a rare form of myeloid leukemia and T-cell lymphoma.
.
In order to be cured, AJ needs a blood stem cell donation from an unrelated donor. However, he doesn‚Äôt currently have any matches on the Be The Match Registry¬Æ. AJ‚Äôs parents are now searching for another miracle ‚Äì someone to save his life.
DNA also plays an important role in the matching process, since patients are mostly likely to match with donors who share their ethnic background. AJ is of Filipino descent, which means his donor is more likely to come from this community. Unfortunately, Filipinos are significantly underrepresented on the registry.
.
Thousands of blood cancer and blood disease patients like AJ need your help. You could literally be their cure ‚Äì you could be the miracle AJ‚Äôs parents are hoping for. Join the registry today at join.bethematch.org/JOIN4AJ or TEXT JOIN4AJ to 61474
.
.
.

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
‚ÄúWhether he is donating or raising awareness, Mainali's goal has always been clear. He wants to save lives by giving something of himself.‚Äù Congrats to dedicated donor Arjun Mainali on achieving 22 donations during 2020, and for receiving the New York Blood Center Presidents Award! Throughout his life, Arjun, who is from Nepal, has donated on 6 continents in 17 countries; from Ireland to Haiti, then on to Rwanda, all at his own expense. In 2020, he made 19 donations with us!
.
Arjun's children have his blood running through their veins, but he also considers the recipients of his donations family as well, and he is proud. "I have a family around the world," said Mainali, who immigrated to the U.S. in 2000. Of his trips abroad to make donations, he recalled one time he traveling to the United Kingdom for a blood donation and then flew back within a day!
.
This year, while in the middle of making a platelet donation, he received a special call, and the timing could not have been more perfect. In his own words, here's what happened:
‚ÄúAround 12 o‚Äô clock on November 24, 2020, I was donating two units of platelets to New York Blood Center. At 1:07, the staff at the center called me. "A 30-years-old patient needs platelets. Your platelet‚Äôs HLA matches hers. Can you donate either today or tomorrow?‚Äù I told her that I was donating blood in Melville Blood Donor Center through the nurse who was taking out my platelets. At that time, Trima Accel Platelets Pheresis Machine showed the required time as 118 minutes. What a coincidence! All the nurses were amazed. My platelets instantly came in handy to save the patient. I felt glad."
.
Thank you so much Arjun, for your continued dedication to helping those in need all around the world, and right here in our own community as well!
.
.

name: Danielle Gross
tweet:
Just back from donating blood, and I'd like to give a shout-out to the awesome tech with the #newyorkbloodcenter who turned my gauze bandage into a flower/bow. 

Here's my periodic reminder/push that if you can get out there and donate blood, you should! 1 blood donation has the potential to save up to 3 lives. Sometimes it feels like there is so little that we can do to help people in this world, but this is something that is so easy! Not only that, but literally every 2 seconds in the U.S., someone needs blood. Be a hero, save a life (or 2 or 3). I've been donating blood since I've been eligible, and it's such a gift to be able to do so. And as someone who has needed blood transfusions, it truly is something that you value when needed. Without donors, we can't have blood for people who need it. At this point, this cannot be manufactured!! So if you can donate, please do it ‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è

name: Daniela Conte Foundation
tweet:
What an amazing turnout we had at our 1st Annual Blood Drive. This year with your help we were able to collect 65 units of blood for the NY Blood Center. That means we have been able to provide lifesaving blood to 195 people THIS YEAR!

The DCF would like to thank everyone who donated and made this possible. We also would like to thank the @newyorkbloodcenter staff and all the local businesses who donated raffle items. We couldn't think of a more powerful way to honor Daniela's life.

Remember, cancer patients are the NUMBER 1 recipients of blood products. It is one of the easiest ways to make an impact. You are eligible to donate every 56 days (or 8 weeks). This means you can donate up to 6 times per year.

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
We are looking for platelet donors! Platelets are very fragile, short lived components of your blood that are essential for normal blood clotting. They must be transfused within 5 days of donation which makes it necessary for us to provide hospitals with a fresh supply of platelets daily. It takes 6 to 10 blood donors to obtain the same amount of platelets we can get from a 1 platelet-only donation. Platelets help cancer patients, burn victims, and many more. Interested in becoming a platelet donor? Learn more at nybc.org/plt #nybloodcenter

At the New York Blood Center (NYBC) we have been working hard to meet whatever blood need rises to the top as quickly as possible.

Convalescent plasma was the urgent need in April, giving way to increased need for red blood cells in May as COVID-19 patients developed blood clots and were put on blood thinners (causing bleeding), and now with NY and NJ hospitals back to admitting non-COVID-19 patients, the regular need for red cells, platelets and plasma for those patients is resurgent.

name: Mount Sinai Morningside
tweet:
Yesterday, Mount Sinai Morningside hosted a hospital- and community-wide Blood Drive!

Sponsored by the Mount Sinai Morningside Diversity Council and the BLACC Employee Resource Group (ERG), MSM partnered with the @newyorkbloodcenter (NYBC) to meet the urgent call for healthy blood donors in New York in the wake of the current public health crisis. Before COVID-19, mobile blood drives hosted by schools, organizations, and businesses made up about 75% of the region‚Äôs incoming blood supply, but all drives had to be cancelled beginning in March due to the pandemic. In June, NYBC began safely holding a limited number of mobile blood drives each week, but they have been far from the 600 drives per month required to meet the need at area hospitals.

Because of the impressive turnout we received yesterday and the generosity of these donors, together we will be able to save 204 lives with our donation.

Thank you to all who donated! We look forward to hosting another NYBC Blood Drive again soon. üëè

name: Jeff Bua
tweet:
‚Ä¢
It took a little more than 2 months but on Saturday, I finally reached my goal of 8 convalescent plasma donations, which is the limit. 

I am told, the 4,864ml (1.3 gallons) I donated helped 23 patients recover from COVID-19. It‚Äôs an incredibly motivating factor to know ordinary individuals like us can be a part of the cure. 

For those of you who have contracted this disease and recovered, I encourage you to donate your plasma. There is a tremendous shortage and this is something you can do to help your fellow human beings. 

If you are symptom free for 14 days and willing to donate, then please do. The process is similar to that of giving blood. After the plasma is separated out, the rest of the blood is pumped back into the body, ‚Äúrinse back.‚Äù So, you don't lose red or white cells. 

You are donating about 10% of your plasma which is a safe amount. And the process takes approx 2 hours from start to finish. Each time you donate, your blood is tested for the Covid antibodies. 

To schedule an appt to donate, call the @newyorkbloodcenter at 800-933-2566. Please feel free to message me direct, if you have any questions. 
.

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
Maybe you have heard of double red cell donations, or maybe you've heard it called an automated red cell donation. Either way, it's doubling up on the giving! With an automated red cell donation, you can donate two units with each visit! When giving a whole blood donation, the collection needs to be sent to the lab to separate the blood components, and then the red cells need to be filtered. With automated red cell donation, the red cells are separated and filtered immediately, making them readily available, after routine testing, for the patients who desperately need them. This type of donation can be given every 112 days. To learn more about this type of donation, and to find out if you are eligible to give automated red cells, call us at 1.800.933.2566 or visit nybc.org! #nybloodcenter
.

name: Centraljerseygirl95
tweet:
There is no substitute for human blood ü©∏. Blood is vital to our survival as it carries nutrients throughout our bodies (among other things). There are many reasons why someone might need a transfusion. These reasons include illnesses and accidents. Many who are eligible to donate do not do so. Donating blood does not harm you and it can literally save lives. Blood transfusions saved the life of someone very important to me years ago. I have been donating blood since I was old enough and I will continue to as long as I can. @newyorkbloodcenter has always been great with helping me through the donation process. You can choose to donate at one of their blood drives or by making an appointment at one of their donor centers. 

If you‚Äôre lucky, you may even get an email like this one alerting you that your donation has been routed to a particular place for use! You will not always get such an email, but it is nice to know that your donation truly had a purpose.  You even earn points for each donation and those points can be redeemed for prizes!  My points always expire because I forget about them, but if you would like free stuff you should consider donating blood. 

To check you eligibility or to find a drive or donor center near you, please visit:  https://www.nybloodcenter.org .

P.S. this is not some sort of sponsored or paid advertisement. I honestly believe in the importance of blood donation. I figure that although I have A+ blood which can only go to folks with A+ or AB+, that my donation frees up a donation of O+ or O- blood which are more versatile and rare.  Thank you for coming to my Ted Talk ü§ó

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
Christian suffers from Sickle Cell and requires blood transfusions every 3 weeks to stay alive. September is #SickleCellAwarenessMonth. More than 90,000 people in the U.S., mostly African-American, suffer from this blood disorder and more than 1,000 babies are born every year with this disease. Sickle Cell patients are usually diagnosed with the disease in their early childhood. Most require frequent blood transfusions to avoid the painful symptoms, anemia and stroke. Patients with sickle cell disease can develop antibodies that cause a reaction to blood transfusions. To reduce the risk of developing more antibodies with negative outcomes, patients need to be more closely matched with special blood donors, but there aren‚Äôt many.  Only 1.7% of donations are able to be used for sickle cell patients. Become a blood donor today and help patients fighting #SickleCell! #nybloodcenter

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
September is #SickleCellAwareness month. This disease affects millions worldwide, mainly people of African descent, but also people of Hispanic, South Asian, and Middle Eastern ancestry. It is caused by a single genetic mutation that affects the shape of the oxygen carrying red blood cells, making it difficult for the red blood cells to get through small blood vessels, clogging the blood flow, and cutting off oxygen delivery to the organs. Sickle red blood cells die early, causing shortage of red cells and anemia with some cells disintegrating in the circulation, releasing toxic forms of hemoglobin that can cause tissue injury. The shortage of oxygen delivery to the organs and chronic tissue injury can lead to serious complications, including stroke and irreversible organ damage. Patients with sickle cell disease can develop antibodies that cause a reaction to blood transfusions. To reduce the risk of developing more antibodies with negative outcomes, patients need to be more closely matched with special blood donors, but there aren‚Äôt many.  Only 1.7% of donations are able to be used for sickle cell patients. Become a blood donor today and help patients fighting Sickle Cell! #nybloodcenter
.

tweet:
Today is Pregnancy and Infant Loss Remembrance Day 2020. Today, we would like to honor a very special recipient, who is now not only an advocate, but a donor herself. Gillian needed 86 blood, platelet and plasma products to survive when she hemorrhaged during childbirth and required an emergency hysterectomy. After losing her child, she and her husband Lou have decided to become advocates of blood donation, to help those in need, and to inspire others who have experienced this loss to keep going. We are continually amazed by their story, their love and the joy they bring not only to our community, but to the world. Today, we honor you Gillian, and are inspired by your continued acts of kindness. #nybloodcenter

name: Belinda
tweet:
Research Chimpanzees Infected, Abandoned, Starved, and Rescued.
_
Chimpanzees infected with hepatitis were dumped on Liberia's Monkey Island. The truth about the horrific lives of these sentient animal beings. Their treatment by a¬†group of researchers from the New York Blood Center was inexcusable:¬†they¬†infected them with hepatitis and river blindness beginning in the 1970s. The researchers fled Liberia during a deadly Ebola outbreak and the abandoned chimpanzees were left to starve. They couldn't be released into the wild because they could spread the disease and didn't know how to forage for food. 
_
Joseph¬†Thomas, a previous¬†caretaker¬†at the researchers' laboratory, steadfastly remained. He¬†came to their rescue¬†and stayed with the chimpanzees when the researchers fled, despite their carrying the disease. He says he¬†"remembers pulling up to islands and seeing frantic, desperate animals.¬†They screamed and fought over scraps. It wasn‚Äôt enough."¬†Thomas now leads a¬†dedicated team¬†of caretakers.¬†Thomas is quoted saying:¬†"They hate to be cooped up. They laugh, cry,¬†get¬†jealous¬†and have temper tantrums‚Äî'just like us.'
_
Thomas said:¬†‚ÄúI‚Äôll be doing this ... until they die or I do.‚Äù

tweet:

„Éª„Éª„Éª
WE CAME TO LIBERIA TO HELP SAVE THESE CHIMPS!!! And NOW under the care of HSUS/HSI these poor chimps are still being neglected! 
_
No shelter, needless deaths and births! HSUS/HSI - Do the Right Thing! 

_
@theirturn @nonhuman.rights.project @newyorkbloodcenter @nonhuman.rights.project @peta @5wfoundation @arcusgreatapes 

@linstagrammo you‚Äôre a hero! Repost from @wilderlandfest
‚Ä¢
BLOOD ISLAND is the story of the New York Blood Center's abandoned lab chimps. 

Deep in the heart of Liberia's jungles in the 1970s, hundreds of chimpanzees were taken from the wild. Captured, bred, and infected with hepatitis, our closest animal relatives were taken to unlock the mysteries of human diseases. 

After the experiments came to a close, the chimps were left for dead on a remote island - before someone came to save them.

Watch this BAFTA award-winning short documentary on WilderlandTV (link in our Bio)

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
Area hospitals and academic medical centers including @nychealthsystem, @northwellhealth, @nyphospital, @weillcornell, @columbiamed, @mountsinainyc, @montefiorehealthsystem, and @catholichealthservicesli are joining forces with New York Blood Center (NYBC) to increase blood donations. Temporary blood shortages are not uncommon during summer and winter holidays each year, but the COVID-19 pandemic has created a chronic shortage across the country that shows no sign of improving. This reality is particularly dangerous given the looming uncertainty surrounding the pandemic‚Äôs trajectory over the course of this winter.
.
New York‚Äôs healthcare system requires 1,500 donations each day to treat patients ranging from trauma victims to newborn babies and their mothers to cancer patients. Prior to the pandemic, donors could stop by community blood drives at convenient locations, but nearly all high schools, colleges, offices and other community groups have had to cancel their blood drives due to COVID-19. Blood donors can now make appointments to visit donor centers, but donations are at just 65% of pre-pandemic levels - well below what is needed by hospitals and patients in our area. Read more at nybc.org/news
.
.
.

 Research Chimpanzees Infected, Abandoned, Starved, and Rescued.
_
Chimpanzees infected with hepatitis were dumped on Liberia's Monkey Island. The truth about the horrific lives of these sentient animal beings. Their treatment by a¬†group of researchers from the New York Blood Center was inexcusable:¬†they¬†infected them with hepatitis and river blindness beginning in the 1970s. The researchers fled Liberia during a deadly Ebola outbreak and the abandoned chimpanzees were left to starve. They couldn't be released into the wild because they could spread the disease and didn't know how to forage for food. 
_
Joseph¬†Thomas, a previous¬†caretaker¬†at the researchers' laboratory, steadfastly remained. He¬†came to their rescue¬†and stayed with the chimpanzees when the researchers fled, despite their carrying the disease. He says he¬†"remembers pulling up to islands and seeing frantic, desperate animals.¬†They screamed and fought over scraps. It wasn‚Äôt enough."¬†Thomas now leads a¬†dedicated team¬†of caretakers.¬†Thomas is quoted saying:¬†"They hate to be cooped up. They laugh, cry,¬†get¬†jealous¬†and have temper tantrums‚Äî'just like us.'
_

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
Meet Ariel - blood recipient, and blood donation advocate. "On March 30, 2012, as I was dropping my daughter off at school, I walked around to the trunk of my car and all of a sudden, a taxi recklessly ran into me from behind. Instead of another day at the office, I was in an ambulance. Instead of listening to the morning traffic report, I was strapped to a stretcher being transferred to a trauma center. 
.
From that point on, as word spread about the accident, everyone offered to help in any way imaginable. People have a wonderful desire to want to assist those in need. I was being well taken care of by medical personnel, but what could the rest of us do? The answer soon came to all of us: Give blood. 
.
To date, I have had 11 operations and received over 70 units of blood. The human body can only hold about 14 pints. That means that somewhere out there 70 people took the time to sit in a donor‚Äôs chair and gave a unit of blood. I‚Äôll never know or be able to thank these 70 people who saved my life. But the least I can do is lend my name to the efforts of those collecting blood donations to replenish and increase our national supply. I want to inspire at least 70 friends, relatives, and members of the broader community to contribute blood. 
.
Then I‚Äôll know that I will have ‚Äúpaid forward‚Äù to others who may one day need blood. Not everyone can give for a variety of reasons, medical and other, but the gift of everyone who does give means so much. Those who can‚Äôt donate can support, volunteer and recruit. You WILL save a life, just as someone‚Äôs blood donation helped save mine." #nybloodcenter
.

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
New York‚Äôs healthcare system requires 1,500 donations each day to treat patients ranging from trauma victims to newborn babies and their mothers to cancer patients. Prior to the pandemic, donors could stop by community blood drives at convenient locations, but nearly all high schools, colleges, offices and other community groups have had to cancel their blood drives due to COVID-19. Blood donors can now make appointments to visit donor centers, but donations are at just 65% of pre-pandemic levels - well below what is needed by hospitals and patients in our area. Area hospitals and academic medical centers, including @northwellhealth, are joining forces with us to increase blood donations. We need your help to support the needs of our hospitals treating patients everyday. Find a donation location near you now - link in bio to search via zip code! #nybloodcenter

name: Jenn Triquet
tweet:
Antibody Testing Now Available!
NYBC will be testing donors who make a blood or platelet donation for antibodies to COVID-19 from Monday, November 2, 2020 to Sunday, November 15, 2020 at our fixed site donor centers only.  As a blood donor, if your antibody test is positive, the plasma component from your blood donation may be processed into convalescent plasma, which is currently used to help hospitalized COVID-19 patients recover. Your red cells or platelets will also be used for patients in need.  A letter with your antibody results will be mailed to you within two weeks after your donation. Remember, testing is only available at our donor centers (not community blood drives). Make an appt today!

https://donate.nybc.org/donor/schedules/zip?utm_source=nybc&utm_medium=donatebutton&utm_campaign=website_links

name: Gabi Rose (enrose)
tweet:
If you tested positive for COVID-19 and have since recovered like me, find out if you qualify to donate so that we can hopefully kick this in the bum soon. Collected plasma may be used to make transfusions for those battling the virus and incorporate the antibodies into a future vaccine. A single pint can potentially save 3 lives and you can donate again once a week for three weeks.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
And even if you didn‚Äôt test positive for COVID-19, hospitals are in need of blood and platelet donations, not just plasma. The need for this is constant, yet the current supply is low. Many restrictions have been lifted and policies revised to reflect the current situation, so if you‚Äôre not normally eligible, you may be now.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Most of us aren‚Äôt medical professionals or wealthy people with the means to support the cause financially. Do what you can.

name: Jessica | NYC Travel+Lifestyle
tweet:
For over 2 weeks, I went through what felt like the worse sickness of my life = COVID-19. I was congested to the point where I couldn‚Äôt breathe properly. I completely lost my sense of taste and smell, and could barely make it out of bed due to debilitating body aches. üò© ¬∑
¬∑
Finally on my 12th day, I started to feel better. And with every passing day, my health was improving. I‚Äôd gone back to my doctor to get retested after 14 days and my results came back negative the second time‚Äîhonestly, I cried as soon as I found out. Testing was extremely difficult‚ÄîI was denied more than 2x before showing worse and worse symptoms. Fast forward, I couldn‚Äôt believe that I beat this crappy illness. Unfortunately, little did I know that I would lose both of my grandparents, just two days apart, to COVID complications. They weren‚Äôt staying with me, so my family and I will never truly know how they caught it. I was devastated, shocked, and in disbelief‚ÄîI still am. üò¢ As much as I wanted to desperately donate my plasma to at least one of my grandparents, time simply wasn‚Äôt on our side. ü•∫
¬∑
I can‚Äôt reverse time, but I‚Äôm grateful and happy to have made the decision to help others in need that have it worse than what I‚Äôve gone through. üôèüèº ¬∑
¬∑
At the end of the day, I hope you guys can look at this photo and feel compelled to donate plasma (only if you‚Äôre able to), and especially if you‚Äôve recovered from COVID-19. üôåüèº
¬∑
¬∑
Together, we can get through this. üíõ

name: Sandra Fuentes
tweet: Keep giving ‚ù§Ô∏è if you can ‚ù§Ô∏è#newyorkbloodcenter #plasma #donate #blesed

‚ÄúYou cannot get through a single day without having an impact on the world around you. What you do makes a difference, and you have to decide what kind of difference you want to make.‚Äù - @janegoodallinst ‚ù§Ô∏èüåé
‚Ä¢
It may feel like the world has been put on pause for many of us, but please remember there are patients still in critical need of donations especially as we face a major global health crisis. Cancer, blood disorder, organ transplant, major surgery, transfusion, and trauma patients all desperately need varying blood components to save their lives. Even if you were infected by COVID-19 and have fully recovered, you can donate as part of the COVID-19 Convalescent Plasma Program. Please consider donating today by visiting nybloodcenter.org
‚Ä¢
Despite feeling like the world has a first class ticket straight to hell, I don‚Äôt think I‚Äôll ever stop trying to save it. As a long term hemodialysis patient, platelet, plasma, and blood donations have saved my dad‚Äôs life more times than I can count. To honor my dad and help patients affected by the blood shortage during this pandemic, I‚Äôll be donating platelets twice a month until I hit my annual max of 26 donations üëç

name: Volunteer Referral Center
tweet:
Our partner @newyorkbloodcenter has issued an Urgent Call For Healthy Donors As Blood Supply Drops To Dangerously Low Levels. .
.
[Source: https://www.nybc.org/news/articles/new-york-blood-center-issues-urgent-call-healthy-donors-blood-supply-drops-dangerously-low-levels/] .
.
Donating blood is safe and it only takes one hour. The blood collection sites are disinfected frequently, and extra precautions are being taken to help prevent the person-to-person spread of COVID-19 as per CDC recommendations. .
.
NYBC staff are practicing health self-assessments prior to presenting at work and are wearing face masks. Donors are also asked to bring a face mask or face covering when presenting to donate. We are also taking all staff and donors temperatures before they enter the workspace or the donation process. .
.
NYBC only collects blood from individuals who are healthy and feeling well at the time of donation ‚Äì and who meet other¬†eligibility requirements.¬†As always, people are not eligible to donate if they‚Äôre experiencing a cold, sore throat, respiratory infection or flu-like symptoms. .
.
To find a location to donate blood and make a reservation, please follow head on to¬†https://donate.nybc.org/donor/schedules/zip?utm_source=nybc&utm_medium=topbanner&utm_campaign=website_links.

name: Tanya
tweet:
Doing good is easy and goes a long way.
.
I‚Äôve been involved in various social projects since school. I saw how people started volunteering and inspired their kids, friends and relatives. Leading by example is my favorite!
.
I‚Äôm lucky to have incredible friends who launch important projects, make real changes in the world and inspire me to be a better person every day. .
So, there was one thing I always wanted to do ‚ù£Ô∏è become a donor and donate blood‚ù£Ô∏è. But I was not allowed because of weight limitations.
.
I watched my husband  being an active donor and becoming a member of Gallon Club (it is when you donate 1+ gallon/3.5+ liters of blood). @art_samokysh just wanted to tell that I‚Äôm incredibly proud of you and your generous heart! ‚ù§Ô∏è
.
I remember going to the blood center with @_geremy_ the day before Boston Marathon. She bravely donated blood to those in need and I was watching her holding a unicorn Spike.
.
There I was... I wanted to donate so badly and could not do it.
.
When the quarantine started, as many others I was locked inside, worrying about the news, moving less, binge eating and gaining weight.
.
Then it hit me! Wait, there is a silver lining to it - now I weight a bit over 50kg (110lbs) and.... can donate blood!!! Yey!!!! üíÉüèª Talk about positive thinking here üòÇ
.
So, today I‚Äôve made my first blood donation in the US together with a friend üë≠ @yapomeha ‚ù§Ô∏è
I‚Äôm feeling really happy and proud of what we did! (Even though I passed out afterwards).
.
As my husband said, life still goes on, there are adults and kids still in hospitals, patients after surgeries and accidents need blood transfusions. There are always people who need help. You can donate too!
.
Check out @newyorkbloodcenter , it is a great useful resource for those who want to do a blood donation and have questions.
.
By donating you are getting:
‚ù£Ô∏èfeeling of accomplishment
‚ù£Ô∏èsnacks
‚ù£Ô∏èdonor points
‚ù£Ô∏èmy favorite - text message that says when your blood is helping patient in a local hospital (+name of the hospital)üè•
.
How cool is that?!? Do good!‚ù§Ô∏è

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
We are so moved by this random act of kindness, and paying it forward from the students of Southside High School. We are so proud to be part of this community, and we are honored to be part of remembering Anthony.
.
"Today, we are taking the time to honor a young man from Southside High School, in my hometown. Anthony Petrocelli should be graduating this year, sadly however, he lost his battle with cancer last summer.
.
This year has already been so unique for the graduating class of 2020. Considering everything that has happened since the spring, many of his fellow classmates, also Seniors, decided to take this time to honor Anthony's life. During a time when the class would be preparing for graduation, or Senior trips, they have chosen to work on this Honor Movement for their friend.
.
Our first stop was to the Blood Center. We gifted each phlebotomist with a $15 gift card to Panera Bread, a BE THE GOOD sign, and a Challenge coin. This is a very special place for many reasons. Clearly they save lives daily. They work hard to ensure great healthcare is given, but this is also where Anthony would visit to give and receive treatment.
.
Shortly after he passed, at the beginning of their Senior year, his friends held a blood drive in his honor. Anthony was very passionate about giving and being a donor.
.
Anthony is greatly missed and we are very happy to be able to share his memories with you, and his spirit."
#nybloodcenter
.
.
.

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
Therese suffers from sickle cell disease. Blood donors have kept her alive since she was diagnosed as child, and she continues to need blood when she has a sickle cell crisis. Today is #WorldSickleCellAwarenessDay. Sickle cell disease is a global health problem affecting millions of people, and in the US, mostly African-Americans. Each year, approximately 1,000 babies in the U.S. are born with sickle cell disease and it is estimated that 100,000 Americans have the disease. There is no universal cure for this life-threatening disease, but there is treatment. Only 1.7% of our population of donors are able to give blood to sickle cell patients. Donors who are African American are more likely to be to be the unique match to treat sickle cell patients. Help us increase the blood available for those battling sickle cell ‚Äì sign up to give blood today! #nybloodcenter #sicklecell #sicklecellawareness #sicklecellwarrior

tweet: New York Blood Center volunteers provide care, attention, and assistance to many dedicated blood donors. name: Paolo Valois
tweet:
Someone gives you life.

Someone saves your life.

Someone nurses you back to life.

Someone helps you find a voice you did not know you had.

Someone welcomes you to a community that you do not know will change¬†your life.

My mother gave me life and her love helps me walk the light.

Six years ago MY DONOR SAVED MY LIFE so I could live again.

My mother's love, nurses, doctors and a web of people in the healthcare system brought me back to life.

My friend Phoebe introduced me to Volunteering, a pioneer step that helped me find my mission, my place in the world and my idea of North by using my own voice.

Being a Volunteer at LiveOnNY and the New York Blood Center (NYBC) connected me to the Transplant Community and allows me to humbly pursue the path and practice of Gratitude and Awareness so I can honor and validate my donor and his family for this new life I was given.

Then you learn to have a life bigger than yourself.

You are free and forever changed.

It's no longer about you.

Finally.

Thankfully.

Help redefine the human condition by using your own voice.

Be Community.

name: Beatriz F
tweet: A long withheld note on American diversity and inclusion following a most humiliating experience with @newyorkbloodcenter . I have always donated blood, I have a rare blood type and have experienced in my family the challenges behind trying to get blood for a transfusion. It is a small token to the community that I take pride in participating in. My experience donating blood in the US had been very positive - after a very strict screening process and some personal and sometimes strange questions I was able to get my donor‚Äôs card and donate. They then contacted me three months later as they said they were in need of my blood type, I scheduled near my home, arrived on time and once again had to go through a similar screening process, which I think is great. Only to this time be DENIED of the right to donate for having LIVED IN EUROPE FOR MORE THAN FIVE YEARS. No, I was never in Europe whilst the mad cow disease was widespread and when looking through their regulations book I found that some of the WILD EUROPEAN COUNTRIES at risk included Switzerland, Norway, Germany, Denmark, France, Portugal.... the list goes on with pretty much every European country included. No explanation as to why. Funnily enough no concerns from me being Brazilian, a tropical developing country with a wider range of diseases, no questions around what I was vaccinated against - in a country where certain religions chose not to have their children immunised. The annoyance comes from the fact that one of the things I have been most positively surprised with when coming here is how American employers have diversity and inclusion targets in their recruitment process, to ensure their workforce is accurately represented, and how they champion diversity in their marketing campaigns. But any European coming to live in this soil is clearly unable to participate in the community. Americans champion diversity and inclusion, certainly, as long as you‚Äôre American. #donateblood #getmeoutofhere #newyorkbloodcenter #feelfreetolookawayifyoudisagree #diversity #inclusion

name: Austin & Howard Mutti-Mewse
tweet:
Mary Howard (born August 24, 1914) played a string of leading ladies during the 1930s and early 1940s, before retiring upon her marriage to Broadway producer and director Alfred de Liagre. Later in life, she became one of New York and Arizona‚Äôs most active philanthropists.
‚Ä¢
Aged 17, she joined The Ziegfeld Follies where she performed with her twin sisters, before landing a featured role in the Broadway revue "Life Begins at 8:40" with Bert Lahr, at the Winter Garden Theatre.
‚Ä¢
From New York, she moved to Hollywood, on a letter of introduction by Alfred de Liagre Jr., to Louis B. Mayer at MGM. A contract swiftly followed.
‚Ä¢
She made her film debut as Diana Griffith in the musical "My Weakness" (1933), followed by a series of bit part roles, including "School For Girls‚Äô" (1934) with Toby Wing and Lona Andre, "The Great Ziegfeld" (1936), and "Bars and Stripes" (1937) with Veola Vonn,
In 1937, she changed her name from Mary Rogers to Mary Howard, and landed the female lead opposite Edwin Maxwell in "Torture Money" (1937), followed by the comedy "All Over Town" (1937) playing the female lead again, as Joan Eldridge, with Ole Olsen and Chic Johnson.
‚Ä¢
Her other feature roles include: "Fast Company" (1938) with Melvyn Douglas; as Mary Tompkins in "Love Finds Andy Hardy" (1938) with Mickey Rooney; director John Cromwell‚Äôs "Abe Lincoln in Illinois" (1940) with Raymond Massey; opposite Frank Morgan in "The Wild Man in Borneo" (1941), and played Edith Keating opposite Robert Taylor in the Western, "Billy the Kid‚Äô" (1941) co-starring Brain Donlevy.
‚Ä¢
In 1942, shortly after the release of the film "The Story of Edgar Allan Poe", she married Alfred de Liagre Jr., and retired to raise their family. After his death in 1987, she continued her philanthropic activities, and was also an active campaigner for The New York Blood Center and various AIDS and HIV charities.
in 2007, she collected a Lifetime Achievement Award from The Arizona National Board of Film, Theatre and Television. Mary died two years later, in June 2009, aged 94.

name: Lia (she/her), Lia Schaffner
tweet:
Today, I donated blood for the first time today. 
And I‚Äôm not saying this or posting about it because I‚Äôm trying to gain likes and followers or get attention. I‚Äôm doing this to tell you that it‚Äôs one of the most easiest things to do if you are at least 17 and meet the medical requirements (which you can look up online).
All you have to do is make an appointment at a donation center near you and once you arrive, the process is fairly easy and simple. In fact. The process of registering was longer than donating the blood itself. 
It took 10 minutes to donate the blood and at the end, I was so surprised. Because not only was it quick, but I felt fine afterward. You‚Äôd think seeing the blood leaving your body would give you multiple side effects, but no, the only thing I felt was a bit hungry and they provided the snacks and juice. 
Knowing that something in your body has the ability to save peoples lives is something to be grateful for. We are all living on this planet, together. And I believe our purpose to help others and if you can, then why wouldn‚Äôt you?
Yes its just a small second of a pinch on your finger (to check if you have enough iron in your blood) and a tiny bit of pain on your arm to draw the blood (the same kind of feeling when you get your blood tested when you visit the doctor); but it‚Äôs worth it, when you think about the lives you are saving. Every day, hospitals need blood. For emergencies, surgeries, etc. People need blood to survive and will die without blood. That‚Äôs a fact. And right now, the only way to make blood is in living bodies. We are walking ‚Äúwaterfalls‚Äù, we are factories that make necessities for free. 
If you‚Äôre healthy, at least 17 and are near a blood donation center, I don‚Äôt see an excuse not to donate blood. (I am terrified of needles and have used that excuse to not donate and I regret that a lot, but really, technology and science have improved to make things like this easy and almost painless). It‚Äôs just an hour of your time. All it has to be is your decision to save lives. 
#donateblood #newyorkbloodcenter #portauthoritymidtowndonorcenter #savealife #savelives #simpleandeasy #donation

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
Have you considered donating a little extra? Check out @bethematch_nybc to see how you can give a little more hope tonthose in need!
‚Ä¢ 
@bethematch_nybc Uzo recalls her donation experience:  Excerpt see full story on our Facebook page (link in Bio) ‚ÄúSomeone asked me right after my donation whether I would go through the process again - I said then and I continue to feel the same, that whatever inconveniences, discomfort, one night of hospital stay, did not compare with the opportunity to  help someone facing a life threatening health crisis. I would do it again and again and hope and pray that if the circumstance were reversed, someone would do the same for me.
.
We asked Uzo the following questions: [What encouraged you to join the registry?] ‚ÄúI was a sophomore in college and attended the Black Family Reunion on the National Mall in Washington D.C. and spoke to someone about the fact that matches are more likely to occur within an ethnic group,  my family had lived with sickle cell through my uncle's experiences and the thought that I could do something as simple as donate blood or marrow to make a difference impacted me - I paused and signed up - that was about 25 years ago.‚Äù
.
[How do you think we can disrupt the disparity?] ‚ÄúI think we have to continue to tell real life stories - particularly donor stories that will combat certain myths, misstatements and misrepresentations, are important.‚Äù
.
.
.

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
We are so thankful today and everyday for our veterans! We'd like to celebrate Veteran's Day by sharing Chris' story with you.
.
Chris is a medically retired US Marine, heart transplant recipient, stroke survivor, and now a motivational speaker.  While in the @Marines, Chris went into heart failure and suffered 3 strokes.  He had 2 open heart surgeries, the first to put in a heart pump, an LVAD, to keep him alive while he waited for a heart transplant, and the second on April 9, 2013 when he received his new heart.  Chris is now pursuing a career in Motivational Speaking and helping others in a similar health situation, both civilian and Military. .
Thank you to Chris, and all of our veterans, for your service. #VeteransDay #nybloodcenter
.
.
.
