name: Paolo Valois
tweet:
With LiveOnNY Team + we, recipients - Bill, Elena and myself - along with living donor Roberta, were Volunteers in a Grief & Self Care Workshop for donor families.

These workshops are incredible therapeutic instruments to help manage their emotional pain, navigate through their grief and the void left by the loss of their loved ones, with the hope to bring the families comfort in their time of sorrow and transition.

As Volunteers, we humbly hope that our interaction with these families may provide them some relief, knowing that the lives of their loved ones continue to live within us,¬†recipients, who honor and validate our donors through relentless work of activism and advocacy on behalf of our fellow human beings who currently wait for a life saving transplant.

Our donors not only gave us LIFE back, they also gave us MEANING. A message of Gratitude to live by and channel and a mission of helping raise Awareness for the cause of Organ Donation.

Thank you  #liveonny for another incredible opportunity to serve the cause of organ donation that saves lives - just like ours, recipients.

Yesterday I donated blood for the first time. Before, I just didn't know how important it is. Once I became a blood captain at my hospital, I learned a lot from @newyorkbloodcenter that one donation can save three lives, and there is a¬†shortage of blood all the time. People can be saved but die due to a¬†lack of blood.

I had to overcome my fear of needles and blood. And I'm so glad I did. It was fast and seamless. I'm planning on doing it regularly, and I encourage everyone to do the same if you can. Even if you can't, there are many opportunities to help. Just spreading the word can be very helpful.

At #NYCPride2019,¬† WorldPride as we celebrate the¬† 50th Anniversary¬†of¬†the Stonewall¬† uprising ‚Äì chez mes chers amis John and Fernando (merci pour l‚Äôinvitation) as we all watched the Parade from up above on Lower Fifth Avenue. There, I was fortunate enough and humbled by meeting Richard (see pic) whose beloved niece Olivia has left us too¬†soon ‚Äì but her legacy lives on due to her family‚Äôs compassionate, kind and selfless consent to donate her organs, tissue and bones to help save lives. As¬†an organ recipient myself,I am deeply grateful to Olivia‚Äôs family and moved by having met Richard. Because of gestures thereof, we recipients can live.

At #PRIDEFEST, as a Volunteer at #LiveOnNY with Monica and Dimple, we teamed up and together collaborated¬†‚Äì informing, educating, sharing our stories and enrolling new organ donors. Amongst the many people we met, WorldPride brought us these two lovely sunny ladies (see pic) who work with organ donation in Australia! 
Today I also celebrate my 
5th¬†Transplant anniversary ‚Äì FIVE YEARS of a life I would have not had hadn‚Äôt been for DONATION. The pursuit of a path/practice of GRATITUDE through Volunteering and Advocacy is a humble attempt to honor and validate our donors and their families, whose consent to donate their organs saves lives - just like mine. By doing for others what others have done for me/for us recipients, we channel the Message of Gratitude and we commit to the Mission of Awreness.¬† I could not have wished for a better way to celebrate this 5th Anniversary! 
We heal when¬†we help.
The Love of my mother lives in me.

Feeling pretty great about giving the gift of life! I have AB+ blood type, did you know that AB donors are universal plasma donors?

Plasma is used to help people suffering from burns, shock, trauma, and other medical emergencies. The proteins and antibodies in plasma are also used to create therapies for rare chronic conditions, such as autoimmune disorders and hemophilia.

name: New York Blood Center
tweet: A donor who donates and then donates again... Meet John Weintraub. John is one of our dedicated donors, who not only spends his time saving lives with us donating platelets and red blood cells, but pays it even further forward. John is also known for donating his rewards points, gift cards, sports tickets and so much more right back to the community. Each donation earns him new benefits and sometimes special gifts, yet John still gives these gifts to those in need. Often times, John will donate tickets and gift cards he receives from donating to the Ronald McDonald House, and to members of his community in need. We hope this double-down on bringing good and joy into the world, and helping out your community inspires you to bring positivity into the world. Be like John - save lives, strengthen communities, be the change. #nybloodcenter #newyorkbloodcenter

name: Cameca Bacchus
tweet:
Current Situation....Blood donation.

New York Blood Center tests for Code 96 and Code 99 to identify rare blood donors. Code 96 donors have a particular combination of antigens that make their red cells rare. Which is what I have been identified as having. 
And if you are wondering Code 99 donors lack an antigen that almost all other people have, so their red cells are also rare.

I have been donating blood on a regular basis for over a decade. If you have never donated blood consider it. * 4.5 million¬†Americans will a need blood transfusion each year.
* 43,000 pints: amount of donated blood used each day in the U.S. and Canada.
* Someone needs blood every two seconds.
* Only 37 percent of the U.S. population is eligible to donate blood - less than 10 percent do annually.**
* About one in seven people entering a hospital need blood.
* One pint of blood can save up to three lives. 
One of those three lives could one day be yours... I guess you could say saving lives is in my blood. 
#giveblood #blooddonationsavelives #newyorkbloodcenter #wholeblood #blooddonor

name: New York Blood Center
tweet:
Meet Tom ‚Äì a dedicated donor who went from giving whole blood to giving platelets when we ran pop-up apheresis drives at the Howell Elks Lodge. And Melissa - a dedicated team member and avid advocate! Melissa met Tom on her very first blood drive in her new role on our team. As nervous as she was, she knew she had a job to do - teach our donors about more ways to save lives, and that is certainly what she did! After talking with Tom about the need for platelets and how to become a donor, Tom made the jump from just giving whole blood in Toms River to becoming a regular platelet in Howell. We were so excited when we recently received this photo of their reunion! We are so grateful for the dedication of our not only our donors, but our team members who reach out to educate donors, and create lasting friendships along the way!  #nybloodcenter

name: Isis
tweet:
Feeling pretty great about giving the gift of life! I have AB+ blood type, did you know that AB donors are universal plasma donors?

Plasma is used to help people suffering from burns, shock, trauma, and other medical emergencies. The proteins and antibodies in plasma are also used to create therapies for rare chronic conditions, such as autoimmune disorders and hemophilia.

Roll up your sleeves and help out! All blood types are needed, all you have to do is make a donation!

name: Tim L
tweet:
Straight from the New York Blood Center- "September is #ChildhoodCancerAwareness month. Oftentimes, cancer patients need platelets, plasma and more to help them in their fight."

If you were ever on the fence about donating, now's the time to jump in and join the club. Putting my jokes and unnecessary Netflix plugs aside, these IG posts continue to drive home the main point I'm trying to make- donating is EASY and it HELPS SAVE LIVES. Look up your local blood donation center, make an appointment, and come through. Heard about a local blood drive setting up shop near you? Stop by and see what they're all about. Still feeling anxious or unsure about donating? That's ok! Then let your friends, family members, and IG followers know what's up and see if they want to make a donation.

Now, if you'll excuse me, I'm going to get back to my Hip Hop Evolution on Netflix, while I make a much needed platelet donation. Today is worse than yesterday. Every donation helps.¬† ¬†

name: Tim L
tweet:
From the New York Blood Center: October is #BreastcancerAwareness month. What you might not know is that platelets are used to treat cancer patients, including breast cancer, when they are undergoing chemotherapy. This month, rock your pink and join us to give those fighting hope!.

I had a platelet donation appointment for earlier this week and had to cancel due to a schedule conflict. Was legit upset that I had to cancel, but I only had to wait about a week to get a free moment for another appointment. Up at 7AM with XL Shorty, had my breakfast smoothie, and I'm right on time for my platelet donation.

There's a million reasons to donate- so sign up and come through. For my peoples outside of New York state (including those outside of the country), blood, platelet, and plasma donation is just as important in your corner of the world as it is here. Check out your local blood center and see what's up.

Today is worse than yesterday. Every donation helps.

Queste proteine sono di diversa natura (come l‚Äôalbumina che eÃÄ una proteina usata abitualmente dall‚Äôorganismo per la sua sopravvivenza) oppure si sviluppano durante processi infiammatori (per esempio la proteina C reattiva) oppure sono proteine abbondantemente presenti nel siero, come gli anticorpi e le immunoglobuline, che sono risposte immunitarie del nostro organismo a insulti di tipo infettivo, che danno la cosiddetta ‚Äúmemoria immunologica‚Äù (che puoÃÄ essere recente o che puoÃÄ durare per tutta la vita) -

name: AVIS Prov.CT
tweet:
Oggi ricorre il 93¬∞ anniversario della fondazione dell'AVIS, associazione volontari italiani del sangue: il 28 Aprile 1927.

Tutto inizioÃÄ cosiÃÄ: "Nel 1926 il Dottor Vittorio Formentano, ematologo, poco piuÃÄ che trentenne, fu svegliato dal telefono. Un suo collega, ginecologo, lo chiamava, con assoluta urgenza, al capezzale di una giovane donna, che era diventata madre da poco. Si era instaurata una incontenibile emorragia e occorreva del sangue con urgenza, onde scongiurarne la morte. Il Dottor Formentano prese la sua borsa con i sieri e l‚Äôattrezzatura per determinarne il gruppo sanguigno e corse dalla paziente.
Si offrirono, per donare sangue, due fratelli della donna e alcuni parenti. Formentano si mise subito all‚Äôopera e, per prima cosa, determinoÃÄ il gruppo sanguigno della donna. ComincioÃÄ quindi con il primo fratello, ma il gruppo non corrispondeva; passoÃÄ al secondo fratello, ma anche lui non era dello stesso gruppo della donna; inizioÃÄ allora, guardando ansiosamente la madre, a ricercare lo stesso gruppo sanguigno nei parenti. Inesorabilmente uno dopo l‚Äôaltro ma il gruppo non corrispondeva. L‚Äôemorragia continuava.
La donna moriÃÄ, senza aver potuto vedere il figlio appena nato.

Il Dottor Formentano quella notte tornoÃÄ a casa amareggiato e deluso. Non riusciÃÄ a chiudere occhio. Un pensiero continuo lo tormentava: possibile non si possa chiedere aiuto a tanti uomini sani della cittaÃÄ, affincheÃÄ donassero una piccola parte del loro sangue per salvare i fratelli sofferenti e tutti coloro che, per mancanza di sangue, erano condannati a morire? La mattina dopo invioÃÄ un appello a un giornale. In esso si chiedevano ai Donatori volontari di sangue, onde far fronte alle necessitaÃÄ degli ospedali: si doveva donare volontariamente, segretamente, disinteressatamente.

Il giorno dopo qualcuno, letto l‚Äôappello, disse che Formentano era matto...
Eppure oggi possiamo contare su piuÃÄ di 1.300.000 soci!

Oggi restiamo a casa, usciamo solo per donare!

‚Åâüìå #IlPresidenteRisponde #AVIS
Sono due esami assolutamente diversi che si usano per scopi diversi e con tempi diversi. Il #TAMPONE, che eÃÄ quello che abbiamo tutti imparato a conoscere attraverso questa infezione da Coronavirus, eÃÄ un test che viene fatto su pazienti (o anche sulle persone sane) e serve a capire se nelle vie aeree del soggetto eÃÄ presente il #virus, quindi se SI HA il virus.
Lo si fa prelevando una parte di liquidi delle alte vie respiratorie (nelle cavitaÃÄ nasali o a livello della faringe). Il #TEST #SIEROLOGICO ci serve soprattutto a capire se il soggetto HA AVUTO la malattia, attraverso il dosaggio degli anticorpi nel suo siero. Gli anticorpi possono essere di due tipi, conosciamo gli IgM che sono i primi che si sviluppano durante la fase acuta della malattia, e poi le IgG, che sono le immunoglobuline anticorpali, che rappresentano la memoria a lungo termine del nostro organismo. -

L‚Äôemergenza Coronavirus ha drasticamente ridotto le donazioni di sangue, le conseguenze per chi necessita di trasfusioni e di interventi sono pesanti. Le donazioni non devono assolutamente fermarsi, la paura del contagio non ci deve condizionare, le uscite per donare il sangue sono consentite.

Come fare?üë©üèª‚Äç‚öïÔ∏è
Le strutture ospedaliere si stanno attrezzando per effettuare la prenotazione delle donazioni, noi vi aggiorneremo sulle stories su tutti i sistemi giaÃÄ attivi. Consigliamo di prenotare gli appuntamenti anche per evitare assembramenti. Una volta prenotato l‚Äôappuntamento il donatore deve stampare e compilare l‚Äôautodichiarazione e portare con se la prenotazione.

Chi puoÃÄ donare? üè•
Deve astenersi chi ha contratto la malattia o eÃÄ a rischio per i contatti con persone infettate. Inoltre chi dona non deve avere la febbre neÃÄ tosse e raffreddore. Al momento della donazione verraÃÄ chiesto di avvertire tramite chiamata al centro trasfusionale di riferimento se nei 15 giorni dalla donazione dovessero insorgere febbre o raffreddore.
